issue.title: Spec no longer executing in geb-example-gradle
issue.body:
## Problem
While playing around with the latest version of the [geb-example-gradle project](https://github.com/geb/geb-example-gradle), I noticed that only the JUnit 4 test was getting run—but the Spock spec was not.

`./gradlew clean chromeTest`

![test results currently](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/25108287/190089281-6f1f6b5e-3fe6-45b9-bd19-c993806702a7.png)

## Investigation
I attempted a bisect and it looks like one of the last places where both the JUnit 4 Tests and the Spock Spec both run is commit bfb1fda8e2e0836fd6c143f81f287fbd6f315ef3.

```
git checkout bfb1fda8e2e0836fd6c143f81f287fbd6f315ef3
<adjust chromedriver version>
./gradlew clean chromeTest
```
![test results back then](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/25108287/190090066-b0c12c35-a556-471d-8fc9-5a5dcd4b42d4.png)

Anyway, I wanted to help out, so I thought I'd let you know!

comment.body:
Oh, a potentially important detail:
When I try to run specifically that spec on later versions, I get the following:
```
$ ./gradlew clean chromeTest --tests GebishOrgSpec
> Task :chromeTest FAILED

FAILURE: Build failed with an exception.

* What went wrong:
Execution failed for task ':chromeTest'.
> No tests found for given includes: [GebishOrgSpec](--tests filter)
```

Merge pull request #20721 Add `jdk.io.File.enableADS` to list of immutable system properties

This commit adds `jdk.io.File.enableADS` to the list of immutable system properties, to enable the property
to be passed on the command line, rather than set at runtime.

Relates: https://github.com/elastic/logstash/issues/14075
Signed-off-by: Rob Bavey <rob.bavey@elastic.co>

<!--- The issue this PR addresses -->
Fixes #?

### Context

A recent update to the JDK, present in `11.0.15+10`, `17.0.3+7` introduced functionality
to check the validity of Windows file paths, rejecting, for example, paths with a `:`
present anywhere other than immediately following the drive letter. Unfortunately, this has the
side effect of throwing exceptions when attempting to write to the `NUL:` device.

This validity check is gated behind a property `jdk.io.File.enableADS`, which is set to `false` for
`11.0.15+10`, `17.0.3+7` releases of the JDK (it will be set to `true` for the next set of JDK releases)
This is causing our gradle jobs to fail, as the property is not set when the gradle daemon starts, as the
property is set after the test to determine the value is performed. This will fail for any Windows builds that
use the affected JDKs, and attempt to write to the `NUL:` device

Relates: https://github.com/elastic/logstash/issues/14075

### Contributor Checklist
- [x] [Review Contribution Guidelines](https://github.com/gradle/gradle/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md)
- [x] Make sure that all commits are [signed off](https://git-scm.com/docs/git-commit#Documentation/git-commit.txt---signoff) to indicate that you agree to the terms of [Developer Certificate of Origin](https://developercertificate.org/).
- [x] Make sure all contributed code can be distributed under the terms of the [Apache License 2.0](https://github.com/gradle/gradle/blob/master/LICENSE), e.g. the code was written by yourself or the original code is licensed under [a license compatible to Apache License 2.0](https://apache.org/legal/resolved.html).
- [x] Check ["Allow edit from maintainers" option](https://help.github.com/articles/allowing-changes-to-a-pull-request-branch-created-from-a-fork/) in pull request so that additional changes can be pushed by Gradle team
- [ ] Provide integration tests (under `<subproject>/src/integTest`) to verify changes from a user perspective
- [ ] Provide unit tests (under `<subproject>/src/test`) to verify logic
- [ ] Update User Guide, DSL Reference, and Javadoc for public-facing changes
- [ ] Ensure that tests pass sanity check: `./gradlew sanityCheck`
- [ ] Ensure that tests pass locally: `./gradlew <changed-subproject>:quickTest`

### Gradle Core Team Checklist
- [ ] Verify design and implementation
- [ ] Verify test coverage and CI build status
- [ ] Verify documentation
- [ ] Recognize contributor in release notes

issue.title: Spec no longer executing in geb-example-gradle
issue.body:
## Problem
While playing around with the latest version of the [geb-example-gradle project](https://github.com/geb/geb-example-gradle), I noticed that only the JUnit 4 test was getting run—but the Spock spec was not.

`./gradlew clean chromeTest`

![test results currently](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/25108287/190089281-6f1f6b5e-3fe6-45b9-bd19-c993806702a7.png)

## Investigation
I attempted a bisect and it looks like one of the last places where both the JUnit 4 Tests and the Spock Spec both run is commit bfb1fda8e2e0836fd6c143f81f287fbd6f315ef3.

```
git checkout bfb1fda8e2e0836fd6c143f81f287fbd6f315ef3
<adjust chromedriver version>
./gradlew clean chromeTest
```
![test results back then](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/25108287/190090066-b0c12c35-a556-471d-8fc9-5a5dcd4b42d4.png)

Anyway, I wanted to help out, so I thought I'd let you know!

comment.body:
Oh, a potentially important detail:
When I try to run specifically that spec on later versions, I get the following:
```
$ ./gradlew clean chromeTest --tests GebishOrgSpec
> Task :chromeTest FAILED

FAILURE: Build failed with an exception.

* What went wrong:
Execution failed for task ':chromeTest'.
> No tests found for given includes: [GebishOrgSpec](--tests filter)
```

Merge pull request #20721 Add `jdk.io.File.enableADS` to list of immutable system properties

This commit adds `jdk.io.File.enableADS` to the list of immutable system properties, to enable the property
to be passed on the command line, rather than set at runtime.

Relates: https://github.com/elastic/logstash/issues/14075
Signed-off-by: Rob Bavey <rob.bavey@elastic.co>

<!--- The issue this PR addresses -->
Fixes #?

### Context

A recent update to the JDK, present in `11.0.15+10`, `17.0.3+7` introduced functionality
to check the validity of Windows file paths, rejecting, for example, paths with a `:`
present anywhere other than immediately following the drive letter. Unfortunately, this has the
side effect of throwing exceptions when attempting to write to the `NUL:` device.

This validity check is gated behind a property `jdk.io.File.enableADS`, which is set to `false` for
`11.0.15+10`, `17.0.3+7` releases of the JDK (it will be set to `true` for the next set of JDK releases)
This is causing our gradle jobs to fail, as the property is not set when the gradle daemon starts, as the
property is set after the test to determine the value is performed. This will fail for any Windows builds that
use the affected JDKs, and attempt to write to the `NUL:` device

Relates: https://github.com/elastic/logstash/issues/14075
